 a woman could attract my brother; so I want to see her with my own eyes.'

'Do you mean to say,' asked Madame Lecerf, 'that you think she is a dreadful, dangerous woman? Une femme fatale?

Because, you know, that's not so. She's good as good bread.'

'Oh, no,' I said. 'Not dreadful, not dangerous. Clever, if you like, and all that. But.... No, I must see for myself.'

